<dl id="n54109c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54109c">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54109c"> 109(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Friday mosque <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54109c"><li>FW 5.24 </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/lexa.htm#n54109c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/l39a.htm#n54109c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54109c">MS BL 47476a-135</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:293 <a name="ad7" href="../../ff/fdra/ada.htm#ad7">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/a/ad7.htm#n54109c">Draft: I.1&sect;1.7</a>/2.7</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">About midday, the hour of prayer, the procession halted, and Mohammed led the prayers and preached to the assembled people. On the spot where this happened is now a mosque, which is known as the <mark>&ldquo;Friday Mosque.&rdquo;</mark>. Friday was chosen, later on, as the day to be specially set apart for the service of God, like the Christian Sunday. <small> Edith Holland, <a name="EHSM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EHSM"><cite title="source">The Story of Mohammed</cite></a> (1914) 90</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
